About the data

Data was collected from 4 participants over 2 hours each performing a particular exercise. The following data was collected, or derived from the acceleromiter readings:

  • For each accelerometer: angles of roll and pitch and the length of the acceleration vector.
  • Variance of roll, pitch and module of acceleration for all samples.

Getting and cleaning the data

trainData <- read.csv("https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv", header = TRUE, na.strings = c("", " ", "NA"))

Did to length of report constaints exporatory data analysis will not be included in this report.

We can see that most of the data is either NA or blank, so we can remove these columns.

#na_count <-sapply(trainData, function(y) sum(length(which(is.na(y)))))
#na_count <- data.frame(na_count)
#blank_count <-sapply(trainData, function(y) sum(y==""))
#blank_count <- data.frame(blank_count)
trainData <- trainData[,colSums(is.na(trainData)) == 0]

Look at correlation to see if we can subset further.

corData <- trainData[,8:60]
corData$classe <- as.numeric(corData$classe)
trainCor <- cor(corData)
corrplot(trainCor, method = "color", tl.col = "black", tl.cex = 0.6)

It looks like there is no strong single correlation between classe and any other variable, so we cannot subset further.

summary(trainCor[-53,"classe"])
##       Min.    1st Qu.     Median       Mean    3rd Qu.       Max. 
## -0.2903000 -0.0453500 -0.0002668 -0.0014880  0.0457300  0.3438000

Split the data into training and validation sets. Removing the first few columns as the model will pick up the index X as the most important variable.

inTrainging <- createDataPartition(y = trainData$classe, p = 0.5, list = FALSE)
training <- trainData[inTrainging,8:60]
validation <- trainData[-inTrainging,8:60]

cross validation and modelling

Split the training data set into 5, this is included in the random forest method of the train command. Using k-folds as there apears to be some time series element.

set.seed(696969)
#folds <- createFolds(y=trainData$classe, k = 10, list = TRUE, returnTrain = TRUE)
model <- train(classe ~ .,data = training, method = "rf",
                trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
                prox = TRUE, allowParallel = TRUE)
